        new TestedOpcode(0x0017, "REQUEST_TARGET",
            "Opcodes/SectorRequestTargetTests.cs RequestTarget_OnNullTarget_ReceivesSetTargetWithSentinelTargetIdMinusOne — client sends a canonical 8-byte RequestTarget payload {int32 GameID=0; int32 TargetID=0} on the sector connection after STAGE handshake completes. Server Player::HandleRequestTarget (server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:3390) unconditionally calls SendSetTarget(request->TargetID, -1) regardless of whether the target exists — for TargetID=0 the GetObjectFromID(0) lookups return null for both newtarget and oldtarget, m_ProspectWindow is false on a fresh starbase character so OpenInterface is skipped, BlankVerbs is a safe memset, and the threat-rank logic is gated on newtarget != null so it's also skipped. The mandatory SetTarget reply makes this a direct positive-correlation test instead of a survival probe — we assert the 0x0019 SET_TARGET payload is exactly 8B, that the reply GameID equals our request TargetID (0), and that the reply TargetID equals the hard-coded -1 sentinel that SendSetTarget emits. Catches: (a) PacketStructures.h RequestTarget long-revert regression (currently 2× int32_t = 8B canonical; if widened to long the struct grows to 12B and TargetID reads from past end of 8B wire payload into garbage); (b) PacketStructures.h SetTarget reply long-revert (caught by payload-length-8 assert); (c) reply field-order swap (caught by TargetID==-1 assert — the literal would appear in GameID slot instead); (d) proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping the opcode (0x0017 is not explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp); (e) server→client UDP fan-out regression in the SendOpcode→SendPacketCache→0x2016 PACKET_SEQUENCE→proxy SendClientPacketSequence→TCP path; (f) dispatcher mis-route at server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:443. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: the wire shape and the -1 sentinel reply are exactly what retail emits when the user clicks empty space to clear the active target."),
        new TestedOpcode(0x0018, "REQUEST_TARGETS_TARGET",
            "Opcodes/SectorRequestTargetsTargetTests.cs RequestTargetsTarget_OnUnknownPlayer_ReceivesSetTargetWithLiteralZeroGameId — client sends a canonical 8-byte RequestTarget-shaped payload {int32 GameID=0; int32 TargetID=0x12345678} on the sector connection after STAGE handshake completes. The retail client emits this opcode after receiving a 0x0019 SET_TARGET with TargetID=-1 (the Wave-19 sentinel meaning \"no rank/threat info yet\") to ask the server for the targeted player's current target. Server Player::HandleRequestTargetsTarget (server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:3494) calls PlayerManager::GetPlayer(request->TargetID); the hash-map keyed on CharacterID returns null for the 0x12345678 sentinel (no seeded player has that ID — SaveManager assigns account_id*5+slot+1, so for our 9_000_017 account slot 0 the CharacterID is 45_000_086 ≪ 305_419_896), and the else-branch fires: SendSetTarget(0, -1) (literal 0 GameID, literal -1 TargetID — NOT mirrored from request->TargetID), then ShipIndex()->SetTargetGameID(-1), then SendAuxShip() (which is a no-op when HasDiff() is false). This is a stronger direct-reply assertion than Wave 19's REQUEST_TARGET because the reply GameID slot carries a literal 0 instead of mirroring request->TargetID — by sending TargetID=0x12345678 we differentiate the correct HandleRequestTargetsTarget else-branch (reply GameID=0) from a 0x0018→0x0017 dispatcher mis-route (which would emit SendSetTarget(0x12345678, -1) so reply GameID=0x12345678). Catches: (a) PacketStructures.h RequestTarget long-revert regression (struct is reused by both 0x0017 and 0x0018 so 8B canonical is shared); (b) PacketStructures.h SetTarget reply long-revert (payload-length-8 assert); (c) the 0x0018→0x0017 dispatcher mis-route at server/src/PlayerConnection.cpp:447 (the differentiator the Wave-19 test couldn't catch — both handlers happen to produce identical replies for TargetID=0); (d) PlayerManager::GetPlayer regression where the hash-map lookup mis-handles unknown IDs (e.g. returning a stale pointer instead of null would walk the if-branch and chain into HandleRequestTarget with a non-zero data[4..7] = stale player's target → reply GameID=stale_target rather than literal 0); (e) proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode dropping the opcode (0x0018 is not explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp); (f) SendAuxShip side-effect regression — if a refactor flips HasDiff() to default-true the test would see an extra unexpected 0x001B AUX_DATA frame in the drain loop (not asserted as failure but provides a diagnostic signal); (g) ShipIndex()->SetTargetGameID(-1) null-deref. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: the wire shape and the literal SendSetTarget(0, -1) reply on unknown-player lookup are exactly what retail emits — the -1 sentinel propagation across both 0x0017 and 0x0018 paths is the canonical retail behaviour and we don't fabricate any side-channel."),
