_linux.cpp:568 tightening (currently passes 0x0047 because 0x0047 < 0x0FFF; a regression to opcode < 0x0040 would silently drop it from the wire and the test would surface a missing-opcode failure); (e) SectorLogin2's call ordering — if SendLoginShipData moves AFTER SendStart the 0x0047/0x0061 frames would arrive past the 0x0005 terminator and DoSectorLoginUntilStartAsync would have already returned; the test would fail with both opcodes absent from HandshakeOpcodes. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: 0x0047 is server-originated — no new client stimulus, no server change, no widened input acceptance. Wave 34 simply records the ground truth that the server has been emitting 0x0047 on every prior wave's handshake without any test asserting on it. The opcode + struct symbol live in common/include/net7/Opcodes.h and common/include/net7/PacketStructures.h (Ship struct ~22B per the SendOpcode call's sizeof(Ship); the actual contents aren't asserted by this test — Wave 34 covers the dispatch and emit path, leaving payload-field assertions to a future wave that wants a typed Ship codec). Passive-observation is a legit ratchet pattern: it gives +N coverage on N opcodes the server already pushes for free, without burning a new client stimulus per opcode."),
