56) — surfaces as either a REQUEST_TIME-still-works pass-through (false positive but tolerable) or as an unexpected inbound 0x0056 frame before CLIENT_SET_TIME. (c) HandleSkillStringRequest GetObjectManager() null-deref removal — current `if (om)` guard at line 1543 protects against a sector with no ObjectManager; removal would SEGV on `om->GetObjectFromID(...)` — surfaces as REQUEST_TIME timeout. (d) ShipIndex() null-deref — the handler unconditionally calls ShipIndex()->GetTargetGameID() at line 1544 inside the `if (om)` branch; ShipIndex() returns &m_PlayerIndex.m_Ship which is always valid for a logged-in Player (constructed in Player::FinishInit). A regression breaking this invariant would SEGV — REQUEST_TIME timeout. (e) ObjectType() == OT_HUSK guard removal — without the guard, the handler would walk the loot-as-normal branch on any targeted object (or null on a fresh char's -1 target) and call obj->CheckResourceLock() / obj->GetPlayerLootLock() etc. — null-deref SEGV. (f) SendOpcode header-width revert at PlayerConnection.cpp:127 — same load-bearing 4B opcode-header invariant as Waves 8/24/26/27/29/30/36; would break the 0x2016 inner-tuple parser and break the REQUEST_TIME reply path. (g) Proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode regression — 0x0051 is NOT explicitly listed in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp's ProcessSectorServerOpcode switch, so it falls through to bottom-of-switch ForwardClientOpcode; a regression dropping the default-arm would mean the server never sees the skill-string frame (diagnostic loss is silent for this opcode but the same class is caught by petition-stuck / mission-forfeit / starbase-avatar-change tests). Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: the 8B wire shape is byte-identical to common/include/net7/PacketStructures.h:781-785; the no-HUSK-target early-skip is exactly what the retail server does — the loot-permission grant fires only when the user has targeted a wreck. 0x0051 is what the retail Win32 client emits when the user clicks