uter switch; on fresh char immediately after SectorLogin GetSectorManager() should be non-null (sector thread is dispatching this opcode); a regression that returns nullptr here would crash later in inner-switch paths but we don't reach those. (i) SendOpcode header-width revert at PlayerConnection.cpp:127 — corrupts the 0x2016 inner-tuple parser and REQUEST_TIME path silents. (j) Proxy SendClientPacketSequence inner-opcode guard at UDPProxyToClient_linux.cpp:568 tightening — currently passes 0x0034 CLIENT_SET_TIME because 0x0034 < 0x0FFF. (k) Proxy default-case ForwardClientOpcode regression for 0x007E — 0x007E is NOT explicitly cased in proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp's ProcessSectorServerOpcode switch so it falls through to the bottom-of-switch default arm; a regression dropping that default would mean the server never sees the 0x007E frame. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: 0x007E with Action=0 on a player who has not opened a manufacture terminal is a legal but degenerate client message — the retail Win32 client might emit this on a UI race where the player closes a terminal while a queued action is pending. The retail server's mode-vs-action outer-switch fall-through to a LogMessage default is exactly the correct preservation behaviour: server doesn't mutate any session state when the player isn't in a manufacture mode. Zero permissiveness added; not loosening any security posture; not fabricating any reply. Pairs naturally with Wave 44 (0x0079 Terminal=0) and Wave 45 (0x007A Category=0) — together they confirm the bulk-UNSAFE flag on the manufacture-action family was overly pessimistic, and surface a new reusable seam-discovery pattern: handler switches on a per-session state field whose ctor-init value lacks a switch arm → default-arm fall-through is usually a benign LogMessage / no-op."),
