entOpcode regression for 0x3008 — the proxy at ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp:415 has an EXPLICIT special case for 0x3008 (only fires during START_ACK fan-out when SectorID > 9999) but for an in-game 0x3008 from the client side it falls through to the bottom-of-switch ForwardClientOpcode default arm; a regression dropping that default would mean the server never sees the second 0x3008 frame (the first one — the proxy-synthesised one during handshake — would still arrive); (g) proxy SendClientPacketSequence inner-opcode guard at proxy/UDPProxyToClient_linux.cpp:568 tightening — currently passes 0x0034 CLIENT_SET_TIME because 0x0034 < 0x0FFF; a tightening to opcode < 0x0030 would drop the survival probe's reply. Per CLAUDE.md server-integrity: primary-source proof — proxy/ClientToServer_linux_stubs.cpp:413-449 sends 0x3008 to the server during the in-game START_ACK fan-out at starbases, with payload `sizeof(player_id)` bytes where `long player_id = m_UDPClient->PlayerID()`. The test is reproducing exactly what the proxy already does, plus a redundant second send — no new permissiveness, no security-posture change, no fabricated reply. The handler's existence in the dispatch list is preservation-load-bearing: removing it would convert the proxy's existing emit into a `default: LogMessage(\"Bad opcode\")` spam line on every starbase login. Strictly safer than every prior survival-probe wave because the handler doesn't even LogMessage to stdout."),
